    formattedMessage:
      "*GOD'S OLIVE TREES*\n(You are God's grafting)\n\n\"If some of the branches have been broken off, and you, though a wild olive shoot, have been grafted in among the others and now share in the nourishing sap from the olive root.\"\n*Romans 11:17 (NIV)*\n\n*LEVEL UP*\nImagine God has a massive, ancient olive tree that represents His family and promises. For a long time, the Jewish people were the natural branches of this tree. However, because some became proud or stopped believing, those branches were broken off. This opened a space for a \"wild\" olive branch, that is us, the Gentiles (non-Jews), to be grafted in.\n\nGrafting is like plant surgery where a new branch is attached to an old trunk so they can grow together. Even though we were not the original branches, we now get to share in the same life-giving nutrients and blessings from the roots of God's covenant.\n\nIn today's world, it is easy to feel like an outsider or like you do not belong in certain \"exclusive\" circles. But Paul's message in Romans 11 shows that God used the breaking off of some branches to make room for new ones. However, there is a warning: do not become proud. Just like a social media influencer can lose influence if they become toxic and arrogant, we can lose our grounding if we become prideful. We are not better than the original branches; we are simply blessed to be part of the tree by grace.\n\nMighty one, you are God's grafted branch. You are called to bring the unbelieving into belief. In an age where people are searching for truth in the wrong places, your life should be a platform that makes others, including the original branches, curious about God again. When people see you living with great fervor in these last days, it provokes godly jealousy that draws them back to the Father. Live with this consciousness now and always: you are a vital part of God's global plan to bring all people back to the tree.\n\n*PRAYER INSTRUCTIONS*\nAsk God for humility, gratitude for His grace, and boldness to reflect Christ in a way that draws others back to Him.",
